50|$|Kaiser {{was active}} in {{politics}} and cultural movements from his student days. Following the formation of Pakistan in 1947, he joined the provincial Communist Party of East Pakistan. He started working as a journalist in 1949 with the Ittefaq in Dhaka. In 1952, he participated actively in the Language Movement. For his political role in the movement for protection of <b>Bengali</b> <b>language,</b> Kaiser was arrested on 3 June 1952. He was later jailed {{for three and a}} half years. Right after his release in 1955, he was again arrested and jailed on a political crackdown on activists. A few years later he was released. In 1958, Kaiser joined as an associate editor of The Sangbad <b>-</b> a <b>Bengali</b> <b>language</b> daily <b>-</b> where he worked for the rest of his life. When the military coup of 1958 put Ayub Khan in power, and martial law was proclaimed, Kaiser was arrested again on 14 October 1958 and remained in jail for four years till his release in September 1962.|$|R
40|$|Malda, North India. (Photo 1951). Rev. Hans Peter Hansen Kampp (1888 - 1963). Missionary in Danish Santal Mission, 1915 - 54. In 1918 {{married to}} Signe Kampp (1893 - 1982), sent by DSM, 1918 - 54. Working places: Dumka 1916, Kaerabani/Tilabani 1917, Benagaria 1920, Narainpur 1925 - 37, Nimasarai, Malda District 1937 - 54. Signe & H. P. H. Kampp became from 1922 {{particularly}} pioneers for mission {{work to the}} Bengali people groups, beginning at Narainpur and later at Nimasarai, Malda District – a work with major challenges due to political, cultural and religious tensions between different groups of people. Significant for H. P. H. Kampp was his respect and openness towards the Bengali culture, religion and social conditions. His great insight {{in this area is}} also evidenced by several books written by him, in both Danish and <b>Bengali</b> <b>languages.</b> From 1954 <b>-</b> 60 H. P. H. Kampp was member of the DSM Board...|$|R
